\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 He had never even in his young student days given the impression of being perfectly}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 healthy. He had always been pale, thin, and given to catching cold; he ate little and slept}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 badly. A single glass of wine went to his head and made him hysterical. He always had a}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 craving for society, but, owing to his irritable temperament and suspiciousness, he never}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 became very intimate with anyone, and had no friends. He always spoke with contempt of}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 his fellow-townsmen, saying that their coarse ignorance and sleepy animal existence}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 seemed to him loathsome and horrible. He spoke in a loud tenor, with heat, and invariably}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 either with scorn and indignation, or with wonder and enthusiasm, and always with perfect}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 sincerity. Whatever one talked to him about he always brought it round to the same subject:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 that life was dull and stifling in the town; that the townspeople had no lofty interests, but}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 lived a dingy, meaningless life, diversified by violence, coarse profligacy, and hypocrisy;}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 that scoundrels were well fed and clothed, while honest men lived from hand to mouth; that}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 they needed schools, a progressive local paper, a theatre, public lectures, the co-ordination}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 of the intellectual elements; that society must see its failings and be horrified. In his}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 criticisms of people he laid on the colours thick, using only black and white, and no fine}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 shades; mankind was divided for him into honest men and scoundrels: there was nothing in}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 between. He always spoke with passion and enthusiasm of women and of love, but he had}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 never been in love. }
